c7z5FTP Command Line Argsz0

c6The following are arguments you may specify on the command line and as command arguments for the OPEN command:

c2R= <RemoteSite> c5:       :2c7The hostname/IP of a remote site. You may leave out the "R=" part and supply only the hostname but it is ok to include also.:0
c2O= <RemotePort> c5:       :2c7The port to connect to (default=21):0
c2D= <RemoteDir>  c5:       :2c7The remote dir to "CD" to.:0
c2C= <LocalDir>   c5:       :2c7The local directory to use (default=your FILES dir):0
c2L= <LoginName>  c5:       :2c7The username to use for the remote site (default=your mail ID):0
c2P= <LoginPass>  c5:       :2c7The password to use for the remote site.:0
c2T= <Account>    c5:       :2c7Some sites may require an account name; most do not.:0
c2G= <GetFileName>c5:       :2c7A filename (with full remote path) to auto get on connect.:0
c2E= <progress %> c5:       :2c7an integer representing the progress display update frequency where 100 = no progress display, 0=always update progress when any bytes are received and 1-99 represents a percentage of the complete filesize, if known.:0
c2Q               c5:       :2c7Auto quit after automated session complete (usually used in conjunction with the "R" command.:0
c2A               c5:       :2c7Automatically login as anonymous.:0

   c6example 1: FTP ftp.wustl.edu D=/pub/aminet
   c6example 2: FTP ftp.uni-paderborn.de D=/pub/aminet A
   c6example 3: FTP somesite.badport.net O=113 D=/myfiles/ L=rakey P=myfunkypass

c2Notec5: :2c7When the O=<RemotePort> argument is supplied, this becomes the default port for the remainder of the current session, until the port is changed by supplying the O arg again, with a different port number. Otherwise, port 21 is the standard default FTP port.:0
